I have shown how numerous sonnets fit the
model of a particular courtier addressing his
monarch in sonnet form, mostly in the late
1570s and early 1580s. She is known to have
love such poetry and to have received it in
large quantities. Oxford is known to have
been a courtier in high favour at the time,
with a dramatic fall from grace in 1581.
So the Oxford-Queen theory makes sound
economic, historical and personal sense
It also provides more than adequate reasons
for the anonymity of the poet -- extending to
his plays.

The 'fair youth' theory makes no economic,
historical nor personal sense, and derives
entirely from crude, unimaginative readings
of the poems by those were fooled by the
cover-up. So they never knew the identity
of the poet and could never have imagined
that of the addressee.)

