For those who might wonder what Paul is blethering about
this time, I imagine he is referring to a thread which I
started back in June 2001 called &quot;Sonnet 112 - from a
Marlovian viewpoint&quot;. It was not &quot;Marlites&quot;, it was me.

I will repost it now, for more than one reason:

1) It will enable people more easily to see precisely what
I did say at the time, rather than having to rely upon
Paul's grotesquely inadequate representation of it.

2) It illustrates rather well, I think, just what Gary,
Lynne and others have been asking for when they suggest
that Paul needs to relate the meanings he finds within
a sonnet to an overall meaning for the sonnet itself.

3) It might be possible to use it as a sort of 'pilot' to
try out how an individual sonnet might be dealt with in
Bob's proposed book. (It is about twice as long as he has
in mind, but as he is allowing two bites, that might work
out reasonably well).

&lt;quote&gt;

*Sonnet 112 - from a Marlovian viewpoint*

As I promised in the 'The Authorship' thread, another (brand
new?) piece of 'evidence'.

The first thing we need to be aware of is that this Sonnet is
the last in a group of four.

Sonnet 109 is - as Katherine Duncan-Jones puts it - &quot;The first
of two sonnets on the speaker's voluntary absence from the
youth.&quot; The words of the sonnet make it fairly clear, however,
that he has not only &quot;rang'd&quot;, but has done something
(unspecified) of which he is ashamed.

In Sonnet 110 we find out what it is. He has &quot;gone here and
there&quot; (or as we might say, been putting it about) and his
affection seems to have strayed to an even younger friend. He
has, furthermore, &quot;lookt on truth / Askonce and strangely&quot;,
which sounds very much like what Marlowe was accused of doing.
He has, in doing this, made himself appear a fool, &quot;a motley to
the view&quot;.

[Aside: the function of a Fool at Court was apparently to be
'licensed' to say things which, said by anyone else, would have
led them swiftly to the gallows. If Baines's report of
Marlowe's sayings was in any way accurate, this is exactly how
he too seems to have acted whenever he had an audience.]

In Sonnet 111, he goes on about his &quot;harmfull deeds&quot;, which,
as Kerrigan points out, are &quot;No doubt the faults recorded in
Sonnets 109 and 110&quot;. We learn that, as a result, his &quot;name
receiues a brand&quot; (something that is very difficult to relate
to Shakespeare, but which would fit Marlowe - branded an
'atheist' - perfectly), and begs the youth, twice, to pity him.

So to Sonnet 112, which goes thus (in Q):

YOur loue and pittie doth th' impression fill,
Which vulgar scandall stampt vpon my brow,
For what care I who calles me well or ill,
So you ore-greene my bad,my good alow?
You are my All the world,and I must striue,
To know my shames and praises from your toungue,
None else to me ,nor I to none aliue,
That my steel'd sence or changes right or wrong.
In so profound *Abisme* I throw all care
Of others voyces,that my Adders sence,
To cryttick and to flatterer stopped are;
Marke how with my neglect I doe dispence.
You are so strongly in my purpose bred,
That all the world besides me thinkes y'are dead.

(1) YOur loue and pittie doth th' impression fill,
(2) Which vulgar scandall stampt vpon my brow,

Referring back to the love spoken of in 109, 110 and 111, to
the 'brand' which his name has received, and to the pity begged
in 111, he says that the youth's love and pity has helped to
remove the pain he has felt at being so stigmatized by the rest
of the world.

(3) For what care I who calles me well or ill,

He doesn't care what people call him, with, I think, a joke
about his having to write as 'Will'. As Booth puts it:

The sense of the clause is obvious ... but the use of this
sense of &quot;to call&quot; (&quot;to title&quot;, &quot;to address by the name of&quot;)
with adverbs is not idiomatic. The unusual construction may
be accountable to a pun on &quot;who calls me Will&quot;...

(4) So you ore-greene my bad,my good alow?

...As long as the youth forgives him his faults and accepts the
good in him.

I am reminded of Edward Blount's words concerning
Thomas Walsingham's attitude to Marlowe, which were of his
&quot;entertaining the parts of reckoning and worth that you found
in him&quot;, implying, perhaps, that not all of his &quot;parts&quot; were
equally commendable.

(5) You are my All the world,and I must striue,
(6) To know my shames and praises from your toungue,

The youth is everything to the poet, who uses the phrase &quot;all
the world&quot; to be able to use it again with a different meaning
later. The poet must find out these things only from him
because...

(7) None else to me ,nor I to none aliue,
(8) That my steel'd sence or changes right or wrong.

...there is nobody else who is alive to him (nor he himself -
who is alive to nobody else) that can, whether right or wrong,
change his well-defended self-image. The idea of being alive to
nobody else (which was of course literally true in Marlowe's
case) is also introduced, as we shall see, to be built upon
later.

(9) In so profound *Abisme* I throw all care
(10) Of others voyces,that my Adders sence,
(11) To cryttick and to flatterer stopped are;

He has buried (deep in his unconscious mind?) all care about
what others might say about him and, like the adder referred to
in Psalm 58, is deaf to anything they say about him, whether
flattering or critical.

(12) Marke how with my neglect I doe dispence.

Now we come to the denouement for all four sonnets. The
'neglect' must be his neglect of the youth which was the main
topic of the first three, and he is now (I think with tongue
planted firmly in cheek) going to explain how it happened.
&quot;Observe how I now excuse my having neglected you&quot;.

(13) You are so strongly in my purpose bred,

The youth has become so much a part of him...

(14) That all the world besides me thinkes y'are dead.

To understand this, we need to look carefully at the words
&quot;besides&quot; and &quot;y'are&quot; and see precisely how Shakespeare used
them in other contexts.

If we look at the First Folio, for example, we find the word
&quot;besides&quot; just over 100 times. These are almost always either
the adverbial 'Besides', mostly at the beginning of a sentence
and meaning, as in *OED* 2.b, &quot;Introducing a further considera-
tion: As an additional or further matter, moreover, further.&quot;
(about 60 times):

Besides, I will be sworne these eares of mine,
Heard you confesse you had the Chaine of him,

or the preposition meaning &quot;over and above&quot;, &quot;as well as&quot;, or
&quot;in addition to&quot; (about 40 times):

Might yet enkindle you vnto the Crowne
Besides the Thane of Cawdor

There are just a few (about 4) where it means &quot;out of &quot; (some
mental state):

Alas, sir, how fell you besides your fiue witts?
or
Quite besides the gouernment of Patience

But on NO occasion is the word used in the sense of &quot;other
than&quot;, &quot;with the exception of&quot;, or &quot;excluding&quot;.

As far as &quot;y'are&quot; is concerned, I managed to find 43 in the
First Folio, all except one (which seems to have been a
misprint for the word &quot;yare&quot;) quite clearly meaning &quot;you are&quot;.
These include two quite well known ones from the Danish Prince
himself:

Excellent, excellent well: y'are a Fishmonger
and
Y'are welcome Masters, welcome all.

So, getting back to that last line - what do we find? Well I
would say it harks back to line 7 (&quot;nor I to none alive&quot;),
and should be interpreted: &quot;That all the world thinks not only
that I am dead, but that you are too&quot;.

As with my interpretation of the Monument's meaning, I have
again assumed that the words as printed were intentional, and
do make perfect sense. But you will see, I guess, why I say
that this is from a Marlovian viewpoint. Everybody did think
(erroniously, we would say) that Marlowe was dead, but there is,
as far as I can tell, no way in which Wlliam Shakespeare of
Stratford could be so snugly fitted into this otherwise fairly
obvious meaning.

&lt;end quote&gt;

For anyone interested in the arguments which were offered to
counter this suggestion (which I am not intending to deal
with all over again), they are all still available, courtesy
of the Google database.

Peter F.
