This is all very well, but sonnets are personal expressions. They are
not meant to make economic, historical or personal sense. They are
usually written because the poet is driven to write. Other readings
may be possible (I've seen some great ones. Marty Hyatt just did one
in Carmel) but they cannot be, I believe, the most important meaning,
or the generating reason for writing them.

I'm sorry I haven't seen all your work on the sonnets. I haven't been
on hlas long but will pay close attention to it in future. However,
although I can quite see the Queen may well have been a &quot;character&quot; in
the poetry, and she might also have been given it to read, I still
can't get over the s/he problem in the first 120 odd sonnets. I don't
believe she is the addressee. She may be &quot;Beauty&quot; in some instances.
Bob Prechter's analysis of a cipher in the dedication to the sonnets,
given three years ago at Stratford, was extremely clever and made
numerous allusions to the Queen (spelt &quot;Elisabeth,&quot; by the way). But
it also unmasked the names Oxford, Wriothesley, Bassana (Emilia
Bassano?), among others. I wish he would publish his findings.

