Yes, Paul. I was jet-lagged. My jet lag usually announces itself in an
inability to sleep. I flew from Toronto to Baltimore to Chicago to San
Jose to Dallas to Baltimore to Toronto. One day I dipped my toes in
the Atlantic, the next day in the Pacific. Three days later I was back
on the Atlantic coast. I was also travel weary, in the sense of Sonnet
63's &quot;travail.&quot; I was helping to run a conference, speak on a panel,
and give readings/workshops to university students. The fact that I am
not yet completely well probably helped the jet lag along, but if you
know that I arrived back in Baltimore at about 2am, didn't get to bed
till sometime later, and had to get up at 6am (which had been 3 am the
day before) to go speak to a college class, you may comprehend better
why I may have been suffering from jet lag.

If you can't, I now understand why *you* don't understand the
arguments of others concerning the sonnets.

Lynne

P.S. By the way, in Canada, unlike the States, there are four and a
half time zones. I traversed three of them on my travels through the
