narrative poems, Shakespeare *never* uses the word to mean
&quot;with the exception of&quot;, &quot;other than&quot; or &quot;excluding&quot;.

2) Shakespeare uses the abbreviation &quot;y'are&quot; over 40 times,
and (with the exception of one obvious misprint) it always
means &quot;you are&quot;.

Therefore, *by far* the most likely two meanings for the
line are:

&quot;That all the world thinks not only that I am dead, but
that you are too.&quot;

and

&quot;That all the world, including me, thinks that you are
dead&quot;

It is my contention (slightly different to what I thought
a couple of years ago) that 'Shakespeare' had *both* of
these interpretations in mind when he wrote the last line.
He was (with tongue in cheek) excusing his neglect of the
addressee on the grounds that:

a) the addressee is so much a part of the poet that all
the world thinks he must be dead too, and

b) all the world thinks the addressee must be dead, so he
did too.

Now this interpretation, based as it is upon the words as
they were printed in Q, and using the meanings that Shake-
peare himself invariably used, makes perfect sense if we
assume that the Marlovian scenario is correct. I am,
however, unaware of any other Anti-Stratfordian or Strat-
fordian interpretation that doesn't have to rely instead
