Sonnet 112 has great Baconian significance. From the beginning of the
Sonnets, Sonnet 112 contains lines 1556 through 1569. We know Bacon
was born in 1561.
(Line 1561 begins with the word &quot;To&quot;, which adds up to 33 in
Elizabethan Simple Cipher, which is the same as &quot;BACON&quot;.) (Is that
Peter I hear laughing?)

Are there Ciphers? Well, maybe, they might be coincidences. For
instance in the facsimili of the original 1609 version, line 9 of the
Sonnet says:

&quot;In so profound Abisme I throw all care&quot;

The word &quot;Abisme&quot; is capitalized and italisized. The Reverse Cipher is
103.
A=24 + B=23 + I=16 + S=7 + M=13 + E=20 = 103. 103 is the Simple Cipher
of
&quot;SHAKESPEARE&quot;. (Peter, control yourself, probably a coincidence.)

Reverse the &quot;Ab&quot;, and then the word can become, &quot;Ba is me&quot;, &quot;Bacon is
me.&quot; (Coincidence.)

Anyway, look closely at the next line:

&quot;Of others voyces,that my Adders sense,&quot;

Meaning? &quot;In so profound Shakespeare I throw all care, of other's
voices (Shakespeare's voices), that my Adders (capitalized by Bacon
for emphasis, &quot;adders&quot; defines as &quot;those who add&quot;, like me) sense
(yes, I am an adder who senses his meaning). (Coincidence.)

Next line:

&quot;To cryttick and to flatterer stopped are:&quot;

This line is self explanatory I think. The &quot;adders&quot; sense the real
meaning, his critics and flatterers are stopped from knowing. Next
line:

&quot;Marke how with my neglect I doe dispense.&quot;

He is saying to notice how he dispenses his message only to those who
he wants to know. (Maybe.) Now the important lines:

&quot;You are so strongly in my purpose bred,&quot;

His mother, Elizabeth, is so strongly bred into his purpose, his life.

&quot;That all the world besides me thinkes y'are dead.&quot;

Of course, she died in 1603, and all the world is unaware that she
lives in him. Sad isn't it?

This Sonnet is one that is significant to Baconians, if for no other
reason than being where Line 1561 happens to land. There is more about
this one that I won't even get into on this forum. But hey, of course
this might just be coincidences. Even though others were playing games
like this with their literary works, that doesn't mean &quot;Shakespeare&quot;
was.

I apologize for the above post. I know it will drive some of you nuts!
:)

Bob

