But &quot;sufflaminandus&quot; has nothing to do with wind, whatever EB implies. A
&quot;sufflamen&quot; (from which the verb comes) is a brake or drag-chain on a cart
or chariot. Jonson would of course be familiar with this complaint by
Augustus, which is recorded in one of Seneca's vivid descriptions of
Haterius' style as an orator. He spoke very fast, with a copious flood of
wide-ranging imagery, not appreciated by Augustus, who presumably shared
Seneca's stated preference for the older, cooler style of oratory: &quot;our
friend Haterius needs the brake putting on&quot;. So Jonson was suggesting that
Shakespeare wrote too fast and with little discipline, pouring out rhetoric
and poetry unchecked by self-criticism. Haterius was, it should be said, the
most admired orator of Seneca's day, as, one imagines, Jonson took
Shakespeare to be the most admired dramatist of his own.

It's interesting to note that Milton, apparently in his youth a keen
theatre-goer, wrote of Shakespeare as &quot;Fancy's child&quot; (i.e. the offspring of
Imagination) pouring out his &quot;native wood-notes wild&quot; - and contrasted him
with the &quot;learned&quot; Jonson.

Alan Jones

