Then step back a bit, and consider whether the antistratfordian insistence
that the author of Shakespeare's works must have been a university man is
not merely misguided but would have appeared so in his own or in Milton's
time.

The antistratfordian argument seems to go something like this:

1. Shakespeare's works display an extraordinary erudition.
2. All university men were extraordinarily erudite.
3. Argal, Shakespeare must have been a university man.

There are many things wrong with this argument. First, even if the
premises were true, the conclusion does not follow from them (Shakespeare
might have been erudite without a university education). Second, the
terms are not used consistently. The &quot;extraordinary erudition&quot; one finds
in Shakespeare's plays could not be explained by a university education,
as most of the works that are generally considered his sources were not
part of the curriculum, and thus the word &quot;erudite&quot; in the second premise
refers to a different body of knowledge (albeit with some possible
overlap) from that which is suggested by &quot;erudition&quot; in the first.
Third, not every person who spent time in a university came out erudite
even in the things a university tried to teach. There are more things
wrong with the argument, but this should be enough for our purposes.

It is true that Shakespeare (like Kyd) was NOT considered extraordinarily
erudite in his time; he was sometimes mocked for his relative ignorance,
or his fans were for being so fond of his unworthy works. However, it is
also true that he somehow or other picked up quite a bit of book-learnin'
from somewhere (again, most of this could NOT have been part of a
university curriculum in his time). Shakespeare must have been a
voracious reader.

