As is usually the case with Miton, a great deal happens in the little
phrase &quot;Jonson's learned sock.&quot;

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I've always wanted to know why Milton used the word sock, and have never
&gt; found a satisfactory answer. Are you saying that Milton somehow used
&gt;&quot;sock&quot; in the sense of muse of comedy? Or the shoes that classical comic
&gt; actors wore? (both definitions from Webster's.)

"/>

The &quot;sock&quot; is to be contrasted to the &quot;buskin.&quot; Greek and Roman actors
used different shoes for different types of plays. For comedy the
&quot;soccus&quot; (a low-heeled slipper); for tragedy the &quot;cothurnus,&quot; a
thick-soled boot. Soccus/cothurnus == sock/buskin. The same actor might
perform in comedies and tragedies, just as a single playwright might
produce both kinds of plays. Jonson is portrayed as a comic actor wearing
a sock -- we are not to assume that Aristophanes wrote while wearing socks
while Aeshcylus put on buskins before composing the *Agamemnon*. Both
Jonson and Shakespeare had been actors, and both are here presented as
performers, but understood as writers. Milton transfers the epithet
&quot;learned&quot; to Jonson's &quot;sock,&quot; and I hope I'm not the only one who finds
that amusing.

While l'Allegro is fond of comedy, il Penseroso prefers tragedy:

Som time let Gorgeous Tragedy
In Scepter'd Pall com sweeping by,
Presenting Thebs, or Pelops line,
Or the tale of Troy divine.
Or what (though rare) of later age,
Ennobled hath the Buskind stage.

While l'Allegro prefers the comedies of Jonson and Shakespeare, il
Penseroso prefers classical tragedy for the most part, with the rare
modern exception (no author is named).

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Given those meanings, I think it could apply both to the author of a
&gt; comedy and the players.

"/>

&quot;Sock&quot; strictly speaking applies to the player; metaphorically to the
author (just as Shakespeare's warbling strictly speaking applies to a
performing thrush and metaphorically to the author). In &quot;il Penseroso&quot; it
is the stage itself that is &quot;Buskind&quot; -- of course one did not signify a
tragedy by placing the entire stage in a gigantic boot; the stage is
&quot;buskind&quot; because a tragedy is performed there; if a comedy were being
played, the stage would &quot;wear&quot; a sock.

Thus one and the same stage can sometimes hold a comedy, and sometimes a
tragedy; the same actor may today appear in a comedy and tomorrow in a
tragedy; the same playwright may at one time compose a comedy and at
another a tragedy. The same reader or playgoer may in a Penseroso mood
prefer tragedy and in an Allegro mood prefer comedy.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
