&gt; my go at it:

&gt; A. Shakespeare's works display extraordinary erudition
&gt; B. Oxford was extraordinarily erudite
&gt; C. Argal, Shakespeare must be Oxford.

"/>

The original was more like this:

A. Shakespeare's works display the most extraordinary erudition.
B. Bacon was the most extraordinarily erudite man of his (or any other)
time.
C. Argal, Bacon was Shakespeare.

Most Oxfordian arguments begin as Baconian arguments to which a
search-and-replace has been done (for &quot;Bacon&quot; read &quot;Oxford&quot;). While a
pretty good case can be made for Bacon's extraordinary erudition, the
Oxfordian case has to be dummed down a bit, as fits the candidate. Thus
Mark Twain could speak of the &quot;real author&quot; as having had the greatest
legal mind of his era, which might describe Bacon, but is just silly when
applied to Oxford. For Oxford the argument is reduced to &quot;attended Gray's
inn for a bit,&quot; which translates to &quot;must have picked up SOMETHING of the
law.&quot; Similarly, Bacon's actual writings reveal a brilliant thinker and
and accomplished prose stylist; Oxford's actual writings are negligible,
revealing a minor poet capapable of the occasional good line.

