To be a little more serious, but very hasty:

We have some evidence of Oxford's legal mind, apart from the fact he
attended Gray's Inn. See Regnier's article ((University of Miami Law
Review, Volume 57, Number 2, January 2003). The plays require legal
knowledge and an ability to read legal documents in the original
language as some of them weren't translated, and Oxford had that
ability. To my knowledge, no one except Twain has suggested that
Shakespeare had to be the greatest legal mind of his era, and I've
often heard Stratfordians say it wasn't necessary to have any
specialised legal knowledge--don't agree with this, by the way--so I
think the article I've given will suffice. One can't have it both
ways, saying that Shakespeare didn't need special legal training
because Shakespeare of Stratford couldn't have had any, and then
asking me to prove Oxford was the greatest legal mind of his time.

Stephanie Hopkins Hughes' B.A. thesis is to my mind the best source
for Oxford's education. It was written while she was at Concordia in
Portland, and shows that Oxford was tutored by some of the finest
minds in the country. You might try to access it.

There is much evidence for his extraordinary erudition. Lawrence
Nowell, his tutor for a short time when Oxford was just entering his
teens, says: &quot;I clearly see that my work for the Earl of Oxford can
not be much longer required.&quot; Oxford's first (extant) letter, written
at fourteen, is in French. Burleigh (letter to Rutland) writes: &quot;And
for my own part, I find that whereof I take comfort in his wit and
knowledge grown by good observation.&quot; These are all examples taken
from *Monstrous Adversary*, by the way. There are many more. Nelson, a
Stratfordian, also says earlier in the book: &quot;Golding attributes to
his nephew, now fourteen, an interest in ancient history and current
events&quot; when he dedicates his translation of *Thabridgment of the
Histories of Trogus Pompeius* to him.&quot; I can go on for months. I can
find better stuff if I look. I just found these by flicking through a
book which isn't even Oxfordian. Would you like more?

For a discussion of prose style with particular reference to the
letter of September 1572 to Burghley, please see Dr. Stritmatter's PhD
dissertation, Appendix N, and tell me what you see there that shows
Oxford to be a poor prose writer. You might also look at Fowler's
*Shakespeare Revealed in Oxford's Letters.&quot; I might add here that
writing business letters usually casts little light on how good a
playwright or author one is, but I think the particular letter that
Stritmatter chooses shows a similarity of style to that of
Shakespeare.

Oxford wasn't a good poet? The example you give appears to be
juvenilia. Have you seen Jane Austen's juvenilia? It's dreadful. Even
writers have to serve an apprenticeship. What about looking at the
following instead:

IF WOMEN COULD BE FAIR AND YET NOT FOND

IF women could be fair and yet not fond,
Or that their love were firm, not fickle still,
I would not marvel that they make men bond
By service long to purchase their good will ;
But when I see how frail those creatures are,
I laugh that men forget themselves so far.

To mark the choice they make, and how they change,
How oft from Phoebus do they flee to Pan ;
Unsettled still, like haggards wild they range,
These gentle birds that fly from man to man ;
Who would not scorn and shake them from the fist,
And let them fly, fair fools, which way they list ?

Yet for our sport we fawn and flatter both,
To pass the time when nothing else can please,
And train them to our lure with subtle oath,
Till, weary of their wiles, ourselves we ease ;
And then we say when we their fancy try,
To play with fools, O what a fool was I !

Stephen May, a Stratfordian, has also attributed the following poem to
Oxford (It was formerly attributed to Dyer, though I understand it was
considered anon till the middle eighteen hundreds. Changes in
attribution are not that uncommon. The Trumpet Voluntary was said to
be written by Purcell until twenty or thirty years ago. It's now
accepted to be by Jeremiah Clarke):

MY MIND TO ME A KINGDOM IS

MY mind to me a kingdom is;
Such present joys therein I find,
That it excels all other bliss
That earth affords or grows by kind:
Though much I want that most would have,
Yet still my mind forbids to crave.

No princely pomp, no wealthy store,
No force to win the victory,
No wily wit to salve a sore,
No shape to feed a loving eye;
To none of these I yield as thrall;
For why? my mind doth serve for all.

I see how plenty surfeits oft,
And hasty climbers soon do fall;
I see that those which are aloft
Mishap doth threaten most of all:
They get with toil, they keep with fear:
Such cares my mind could never bear.

Content I live, this is my stay;
I seek no more than may suffice;
I press to bear no haughty sway;
Look, what I lack my mind supplies.
Lo, thus I triumph like a king,
Content with that my mind doth bring.

Some have too much, yet still do crave;
I little have, and seek no more.
They are but poor, though much they have,
And I am rich with little store;
They poor, I rich; they beg, I give;
They lack, I leave; they pine, I live.

I laugh not at another's loss,
I grudge not at another's gain;
No worldly waves my mind can toss;
My state at one doth still remain:
I fear no foe, I fawn no friend;
I loathe not life, nor dread my end.

Some weigh their pleasure by their lust,
Their wisdom by their rage of will;
Their treasure is their only trust,
A cloakd craft their store of skill;
But all the pleasure that I find
Is to maintain a quiet mind.

My wealth is health and perfect ease,
My conscience clear my chief defence;
I neither seek by bribes to please,
Nor by deceit to breed offence:
Thus do I live; thus will I die;
Would all did so as well as I!

This is one of the most enduring and popular poems in the English
language. It is also, imo, a fine piece of work though not as good as
some of his later sonnets. Sorry, couldn't resist that. :)

Respectfully submitted,
Lynne

