Of course, the lark in &quot;L'Allegro&quot; is a sky lark (Alauda arvensis), not
a horned lark (Eremophila alpestris). In any case, I was referring not
to actual birds but to poetic birds; so far as I know, the standard
poetic figure in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries had the lark
singing, never warbling.

Oddly enough, in the late eighteenth and early nineteenth centuries the
lark did indeed begin to warble, as noted by Wordsworth (&quot;I heard the
sky-lark warbling in the sky&quot; -- where else?), Burns (&quot;O, stay, sweet
warbling wood-lark, stay&quot;), Thomas Gray (&quot;But chief the sky-lark warbles
high&quot;), and others. (Not Shelley, though -- the Skylark of his Ode
warbleth not).

The warbling lark also appeared in other countries: Mller's _Die Schne
Mllerin_ contains the line &quot;Die Lerche wirbelt in der Luft.&quot; I can't
find a single warbling lark before 1750, though. Counterexamples are
welcomed.

Poetic sky larks are associated with three distinct characteristics:
they sing in flight, they fly straight up, and they appear at daybreak -
thus Milton: &quot;To hear the Lark begin his flight,/And singing startle the
dull night/From his watch-towre in the skies,/Till the dappled dawn doth
rise&quot; (cf. Shakespeare's Sonnet 29). The fact that the Shakespeare-bird
has none of these characteristics indicates that Milton is not imagining
him as a lark.

--
Mark Steese
