"/>

How you understand the word is irrelevant to the question of how Milton
understood the word, and from the evidence of his poetry, we may safely
infer that he did not understand it as applying to the song of the sky
lark.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; And now you've managed to reduce Milton to &quot;standard poetic figures&quot;.
&gt; The only poets who use &quot;standard poetic figures&quot; are bad poets.

"/>

Like William Shakespeare?

Haply I think on thee, and then my state
Like to the lark at break of day arising
From sullen earth, sings hymns at heaven's gate...

The way we determine standard poetic figures is by studying the works of
poets: a figure becomes standard when it is employed by many different
poets. I hope it doesn't come as too much of a surprise to you to learn
that in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries it was common for poets
to write so as to be understood by their readers. It happens that a
contemporary reader of &quot;L'Allegro,&quot; reading the lines about Shakespeare,
would infer that Milton was likening the poet to a songbird, but would
not infer that Milton might have been thinking of a sky lark.

If Milton had wanted the reader to think he was likening Shakespeare to
a sky lark, he had a number of devices at his disposal; he could have
used the word 'lark'; he could have made reference to singing while
ascending vertically; he could have made reference to singing at the
break of day. Milton was not in the habit of forcing his readers to
play twenty questions with him.

A modern reader, unfamiliar with the poetic tropes and figures used in
the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, might well think Milton's
warbler of native wood-notes wild was a sky lark, or even a nightingale,
but that only demonstrates how wide the gap is between our time and
Milton's. Milton had a deep respect for poetic tradition; the fact that
he used standard poetic figures is as unsurprising as the fact that he
used standard parts of speech.
--
