There is nothing here that alludes to a specific bird. What Milton alludes
to is SONG. Specifically, the song-like character of Shakespeare's
verse. Milton in his other poems finds that birds, brooks, springs and
people can sing and warble, therefore it is logical to assume that
he had, in the back of his mind, all or some those things in mind when he said
that Shakespeare could &quot;warble&quot;. The train of connections is

Shakespeare-----------&gt; singing (not Shakespeare---------------&gt;bird), and
then singing------------&gt;birds, brooks, people; and then
| birds--------------------&gt;larks, nightingales, any birds that sing and
----| brooks----------------&gt;any of the brooks or streams that he knew
| people---------------&gt;the singing of groups and individuals and
individual singer--------------------&gt; Shakespeare

And all of this has to fit into

Rhyme with &quot;child&quot;----------------&gt;&quot;wild&quot;
&quot;wild&quot;---------------&gt; nature
nature-----------&gt; the woods
the woods-----------------&gt;&quot;wood-notes&quot;
alliteration with &quot;wood&quot;-----------------&gt;&quot;warble&quot; and
&quot;warble&quot;----------------&gt;singing, which also connects to &quot;notes&quot;.

That seems to me to be a reasonable conjecture of how the
general thought process went, but of course all of this could
happen unconsciously in an instant. But this is the poet's
point of view, not the pedant's. The pedant will try mightily
to shoe horn a thrush and only a thrush into these lines, but
that simply limits the lines to something other than what
the poet intended.

